      "content": "The RecursionError is a common issue when dealing with deeply nested dictionaries. You can achieve the same result iteratively using a stack-based approach. Here's an example of how you can refactor your code:\n\n```python\ndef nested_dict_to_list(nested_dict, prefix=''):\n    stack = [(nested_dict, prefix)]\n    result = []\n    \n    while stack:\n        current_dict, current_prefix = stack.pop()\n        \n        for key, value in current_dict.items():\n            new_key = f\"{current_prefix}{key}\" if current_prefix else key\n            \n            if isinstance(value, dict):\n                stack.append((value, new_key))\n            else:\n                result.append((new_key, value))\n                \n    return result\n```\n\nThis function uses a stack to keep track of the dictionaries to be processed, similar to how a recursive function would work. However, it avoids the recursion limit by processing dictionaries in a loop. The result is a list of tuples, where each tuple contains a key-value pair from the original dictionary.\n\nYou can use this function like this:\n\n```python\nnested_dict = {\n    'a': 1,\n    'b': {\n        'c': 2,\n        'd': {\n            'e': 3",
